<HEADLINE>
<P>
TENNIS / EVERT CUP; GRAF SWEEPS PAST GIGI FERNANDEZ 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JERRY CROWE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Gigi Fernandez, celebrating her 30th birthday, blew out the candles on a 
birthday cake at a party Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
 Earlier in the day, top-ranked Steffi Graf blew out Fernandez, 6-1, 6-2, in 
the first round of the Evert Cup at Hyatt Grand Champions, completing her day's 
work on the stadium court in only 47 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
 "I hired a bodyguard to club her in the knee, but he didn't show up," 
Fernandez said at a postmatch news conference, where she wore a red T-shirt 
with the inscription: "Me? 30? I Demand a Recount." 
</P>
<P>
 Whether it was her advancing age or, more likely, Graf's brilliant play, 
Fernandez showed her frustration during the match more than once. 
</P>
<P>
 During a changeover after winning the seventh game of the second set, 
Fernandez remained in her seat and read a newspaper, to Graf's amusement, while 
Graf stood at the baseline, waiting to serve. 
</P>
<P>
 "She was reading the money section," Graf said, "so I was thinking, she's 
thinking about how she's going to use the prize money she's going to get for 
losing in the first round." 
</P>
<P>
 Confirmed Fernandez: "I was reading stock quotes." 
</P>
<P>
 Why? 
</P>
<P>
 "Just to get my mind off it, try to relax a little bit," said Fernandez, who 
earned $2,650. "I should have done it earlier. When you're down, 6-1, 5-2, you 
have to try to do something different." 
</P>
<P>
 Graf, who has lost only twice in her last 63 matches and has yet to drop a set 
in 13 matches this year, moved into today's second round against Tracy Austin, 
who 11 years ago defeated Graf in the German's first professional match, 6-4, 
6-0, at Filderstadt, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
 Austin said Monday she had fond memories of the then 13-year-old Graf, saying 
she was impressed with Graf's ability and confidence. 
</P>
<P>
 "Is that so?" Graf said Tuesday, appearing to be suspicious. "She said 
something different afterward." 
</P>
<P>
 She wasn't gracious? 
</P>
<P>
 "She said something to the press that I wasn't liking at the time," Graf said. 
"She said there were hundreds of players like me in America." 
</P>
<P>
 Pausing, Graf smiled. "Probably not anymore." 
</P>
</TEXT>
