<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL DAILY REPORT; ANGELS; SNOW SIGNS PACT, SALMON IS CLOSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB NIGHTENGALE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Angel first baseman J.T. Snow, who resurrected memories of Wally World with 
his torrid rookie start last season, signed a one-year contract Tuesday for 
$200,000 and $25,000 in incentives. 
</P>
<P>
 The Angels also are on the verge of signing right fielder Tim Salmon to a 
three- or four-year contract, the largest contract given to any second-year 
player in Angel history. Salmon, the American League's rookie of the year last 
season, is being offered $4 million over three years and about $7 million over 
four years. The deal is expected to be consummated perhaps as early as 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Angel General Manager Bill Bavasi also continues to remain optimistic in his 
attempts to sign starter Mark Langston to a three-year contract extension with 
an option year for the fourth season. Bavasi and Arn Tellem, Langston's agent, 
are scheduled to meet later this week. 
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, Snow hopes that a consistent season will provide the kind of 
offensive numbers that merit a multiyear career for him. 
</P>
<P>
 "I have a much better idea what to expect this time around," Snow said. "I had 
such a great start last year, and by midseason, I felt like I already played a 
full season." 
</P>
<P>
 Snow, who was acquired in the Jim Abbott trade with the New York Yankees, 
opened the season batting .407 with six homers and 17 RBIs in the first 15 
games. Yet, he was in the minor leagues by the end of July, and wound up 
hitting .241 with 16 homers and 57 RBIs for the season. 
</P>
<P>
 "Last year, I was under such a microscope," said Snow, who got married in the 
off-season. "It was a very difficult year for me to handle. I think this year 
will be different. I can come into camp without having people check me out all 
the time. If anything, the spotlight is going to be on Bo (Jackson) and Tim 
(Salmon)." 
</P>
<P>
 The Angels also signed utility infielder Rod Correia to a one-year contract 
Tuesday, and now are left with only six unsigned players on their 40-man 
roster. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Bo Jackson, who wowed the crowd Tuesday by hitting three consecutive home runs 
in batting practice, said he recently signed a movie contract for his life 
story. He is scheduled to meet with a Hollywood scriptwriter during the next 
four days, with production expected to begin this year. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're still not sure who's going to play me," Jackson said, "but it might be 
(Morris Chestnut) from 'Boyz N the Hood.' I'm looking forward to it." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Apparently, it takes time for news to reach these parts: 
</P>
<P>
 While there still is a designated parking spot in the front row at Tempe 
Diablo Stadium for Whitey Herzog, who resigned seven weeks ago, there is none 
for Bavasi, the new general manager. 
</P>
<P>
 Bavasi has yet to park in Herzog's spot.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Manager Buck Rodgers, on the evolution of players' physical fitness for spring 
training: "There's so much money to be made, players are working out all winter 
now. In my first two years, I had to work in the off-season by selling cars and 
real estate. I had no choice because our children had this bad habit of eating 
in the winter time." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Rodgers is scheduled to give depositions in two weeks involving his 
$25-million lawsuit stemming from the Angels' 1992 bus crash. A hearing is 
expected in November or December. BOB NIGHTENGALE 
</P>
</TEXT>
